%% Architecture Decision Record: LangChain Package Migration

%% This diagram visually documents a critical engineering decision made during
%% Phase 5 of the AutoResolve build: the migration away from legacy monolithic
%% libraries toward a modern, modular dependency strategy.
%% Key Architectural Concepts Represented:
%% - Legacy Monolithic Architecture: Historically, AI applications relied on
%%   langchain-community, a massive, bloated package containing hundreds of
%%   third-party integrations (OpenAI, Anthropic, LiteLLM, etc.). Installing this
%%   monolith in a production environment introduces severe risks, including
%%   dependency conflicts (which caused the Pytest errors in Phase 5), slower
%%   cold-start times, and an unnecessarily large attack surface.
%% - Modern Enterprise Architecture: The system now strictly utilizes langchain-core
%%   as the foundational engine. Integrations are handled via specialized, decoupled
%%   micro-packages (such as langchain-litellm). This approach guarantees strict
%%   version control, faster Docker image builds, and enhanced operational security
%%   by only installing the exact code the system executes.

graph TD
    subgraph Legacy Monolithic Architecture
        LC[langchain-community] --> O[OpenAI]
        LC --> A[Anthropic]
        LC --> L[LiteLLM]
        LC --> M[Many Others...]
    end

    subgraph Modern Enterprise Architecture
        Core[langchain-core] --> LCL[langchain-litellm]
        Core --> LCO[langchain-openai]
        LCL --> ChatLiteLLM
    end
</file>

<file path="diagrams/ai-orchestration-workflow.mmd">
%% AutoResolve AI Orchestration & Reasoning Component Architecture Diagram (Level 3)

%% This Level 3 Component Architecture diagram details the internal application
%% logic, data flow, and control mechanisms of the AutoResolve AI orchestrator.
%% It illustrates how incoming alerts are securely ingested, processed by a stateful
%% multi-agent system, and converted into actionable remediations while enforcing
%% strict execution guardrails.

%% Key Subsystems & Workflows:
%% - Edge Security & Ingestion: Webhook alerts originating from Prometheus are
%%   intercepted by a FastAPI gateway. This layer ensures authenticity via HMAC
%%   signature validation and enforces rate limiting before publishing the structured
%%   alert payload to an Apache Kafka EventBus for asynchronous processing.
%% - LangGraph Agent Memory Loop: The core orchestration logic operates as a state
%%   machine managed by LangGraph. It features three specialized agents—Triage,
%%   Investigate, and Resolve—that iteratively read from and mutate a shared, typed
%%   graph memory state, ensuring full context retention throughout the incident lifecycle.
%% - Agnostic Reasoning Layer: To prevent vendor lock-in and ensure high availability,
%%   the agents do not call LLM APIs directly. Instead, they route requests through a
%%   LiteLLM Proxy, configured to use Anthropic's Claude 3.5 Sonnet as the primary
%%   reasoning engine, with OpenAI's GPT-4o configured as an automatic fallback.
%% - Data Retrieval & Context (MCP/RAG): During the investigation and resolution phases,
%%   agents gather deterministic context using read-only Model Context Protocol (MCP)
%%   clients connected to Kubernetes (for logs/traces) and Prometheus (for metrics).
%%   Additionally, a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) pipeline queries a Qdrant
%%   Vector Database to fetch semantically similar historical runbooks.
%% - Execution Guardrails: Before any state-mutating action is taken (such as drafting
%%   a Pull Request via the GitHub MCP), the Resolution Agent's output must pass through
%%   a strict Pydantic Output Parser. If the LLM generates hallucinated or malformed
%%   output, the guardrail fails the action and loops back to the agent for
%%   self-correction, ensuring system safety and reliability.

graph TD
    subgraph Edge_Security
        Webhook[Prometheus Webhook] -->|HMAC Sig| FastAuth[FastAPI Auth & Rate Limiter]
        FastAuth -->|Push Event| EventBus[(Kafka Queue)]
    end

    subgraph LangGraph_Agent_Memory_Loop
        EventBus --> Triage[Triage Agent]
        Triage <-->|Mutate| State[(Typed Graph Memory)]
        Triage --> Investigate[Investigate Agent]
        Investigate <-->|Read/Mutate| State
        Investigate --> Resolve[Resolution Agent]
        Resolve <-->|Read/Mutate| State
    end

    subgraph Agnostic_Reasoning_Layer
        Triage -.-> LLM[LiteLLM Proxy]
        Investigate -.-> LLM
        Resolve -.-> LLM
        LLM -->|Primary| Claude[Claude 3.5 Sonnet]
        LLM -->|Fallback| GPT4[OpenAI GPT-4o]
    end

    subgraph Data_Retrieval_Layer
        Investigate -->|MCP Client| MCP_K8s[K8s MCP: Logs/Traces]
        Investigate -->|MCP Client| MCP_Prom[Prometheus MCP: Metrics]
        Resolve -->|RAG| VectorDB[(Qdrant: Runbooks)]
    end
    
    subgraph Execution_Guardrails
        Resolve --> Guardrail[Pydantic Output Parser]
        Guardrail -->|Fail| Resolve
        Guardrail -->|Pass| Github[GitHub MCP: Draft PR]
    end
</file>

