<file path="diagrams/ingestion-gateway.mmd">
%% Ingestion Architecture & State Flow

%% This diagram details the critical boundary layer between external monitoring
%% infrastructure and the AutoResolve internal event bus. It maps the exact
%% lifecycle of an incoming alert webhook, highlighting how the system ensures
%% data integrity and high availability before the AI agents are ever invoked.

%% Key Mechanisms Illustrated:
%% - Webhook Reception: The flow begins when Prometheus Alertmanager sends an
%%   alert payload via a POST request to the FastAPI Gateway.
%% - Strict Schema Validation: Before any processing occurs, the payload is
%%   intercepted by a Pydantic Guardrail. If the alert is malformed or missing
%%   required fields, the gateway immediately rejects it with a 422 Unprocessable
%%   Entity error, protecting downstream systems from invalid state.
%% - Asynchronous Handoff: Validated payloads are passed to the AIOKafkaProducer,
%%   which publishes the event to the incidents Kafka topic. Once successfully
%%   published, the gateway immediately returns a 202 Accepted response to
%%   Prometheus, decoupling the fast ingestion path from the slower LLM reasoning
%%   process.
%% - Resilience & Fallback: If the Kafka broker is unavailable, the gateway
%%   gracefully catches the failure and returns a 503 Service Unavailable. This
%%   explicit error code signals Alertmanager (or the on-call routing system like
%%   PagerDuty) to bypass AutoResolve and fall back to alerting a human engineer
%%   directly.

graph TD
    P[Prometheus Alertmanager] -->|POST /webhook| F[FastAPI Gateway]
    
    subgraph FastAPI Runtime
        F -->|Validate| S[Pydantic Guardrail]
        S -->|Validation Error| R422[422 Unprocessable Entity]
        S -->|Pass| K_Prod[AIOKafkaProducer]
    end
    
    K_Prod -->|Publish Event| Topic[(Kafka Topic: 'incidents')]
    Topic -.->|Consumed by| LangGraph[LangGraph Agent Swarm]
    K_Prod -->|Success| R202[202 Accepted]
    
    %% Fallback
    K_Prod -->|Broker Down| R503[503 Service Unavailable -> Fallback to Human]
</file>

<file path="diagrams/langgraph-state-machine.mmd">
%% LangGraph State Machine Architecture

%% This diagram maps out the multi-agent cyclic orchestration flow running inside the
%% LangGraph worker. It highlights how AutoResolve functions as a deterministic,
%% stateful reactive system by mapping individual node executions to conditional and
%% cyclic edges based on the updated IncidentState memory dictionary.

%% Detailed Workflow & Core States:
%% - Ingestion to Triage: The workflow is triggered by an incoming event consumed from
%%   the Kafka incidents topic. The system transitions into the TriageNode, which
%%   internally evaluates the event payload via parallel sub-steps (Analyze_Severity
%%   and Determine_Routing) to judge whether it represents an actionable alert or
%%   transient noise.
%% - Routing Decisions: * If the alert is deemed a False Positive (Noise), it routes
%%   directly to the ReportNode to be silenced, avoiding alert fatigue for the
%%   engineering team.
%%   - If it is validated as a Critical / Warning incident, the graph transitions to
%%     the InvestigationNode.
%% - Cyclic Self-Correction & Reasoning Loop: * The Investigation Loop: The
%%   InvestigationNode gathers diagnostic details (via Prometheus/Kubernetes MCP
%%   servers). If it analyzes the data and finds it needs more diagnostic data, it
%%   executes a cyclic edge back to itself until logs/metrics are fully gathered.
%%   - The Remediation Loop: Once the context is set, control shifts to the
%%     ResolutionNode to draft a fix using historical runbook context, passing it to
%%     the ExecutionNode to generate a patch.
%%   - The Human-in-the-Loop Review: The drafted patch reaches the ReviewNode
%%     (mirroring the Slack approval webhook step). If a human engineer rejects the
%%     solution, a cyclic loop sends control back to the ExecutionNode to rewrite the
%%     remediation, preventing broken configurations from reaching production. If
%%     approved, it flows into the final ReportNode where the incident state compiles
%%     an aftermath report before concluding.

stateDiagram-v2
    direction TB
    [*] --> TriageNode: Incoming Kafka Event
    
    state TriageNode {
        direction LR
        Analyze_Severity --> Determine_Routing
    }
    
    TriageNode --> InvestigationNode: Critical / Warning
    TriageNode --> ReportNode: False Positive (Noise)
    
    InvestigationNode --> ResolutionNode: Logs Gathered
    InvestigationNode --> InvestigationNode: Needs More Context (Cyclic)
    
    ResolutionNode --> ExecutionNode: Fix Identified
    ExecutionNode --> ReviewNode: PR Drafted
    
    ReviewNode --> ExecutionNode: Rejected (Rewrite Fix)
    ReviewNode --> ReportNode: Approved (LGTM)
    
    ReportNode --> [*]: End (Wait for Human)
</file>

